<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 2 · Lesson 2.15</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Parallel Structure</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to keep every element in a list, comparison, or paired construction in the same grammatical form — the principle that makes sentences feel balanced, clear, and correct.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What parallel structure means</div>
  <div class="body-text">Parallel structure requires that items joined by coordinating conjunctions (and, but, or) or paired conjunctions (not only…but also, either…or, both…and) must be in the <strong>same grammatical form</strong>. If the first item is a noun, all items must be nouns. If it's an infinitive, all must be infinitives. If it's a gerund (-ing), all must be gerunds.</div>
  <div class="pattern-grid">
    <div class="pattern-card">
      <div class="pattern-title">List parallelism</div>
      <div class="pattern-body">All items in a series must share the same grammatical form.</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex wrong-ex">✗ "The program focuses on reading, writing, and to develop critical thinking."</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex right-ex">✓ "The program focuses on reading, writing, and developing critical thinking."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pattern-card">
      <div class="pattern-title">Comparison parallelism</div>
      <div class="pattern-body">Both sides of a comparison must have matching grammatical structure.</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex wrong-ex">✗ "She prefers hiking to when she swims."</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex right-ex">✓ "She prefers hiking to swimming."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pattern-card">
      <div class="pattern-title">Paired conjunction parallelism</div>
      <div class="pattern-body">With not only…but also / either…or / both…and / neither…nor — the element after each conjunction must match.</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex wrong-ex">✗ "The study was not only large but also it was rigorous."</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex right-ex">✓ "The study was not only large but also rigorous."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pattern-card">
      <div class="pattern-title">Verb phrase parallelism</div>
      <div class="pattern-body">When two or more verb phrases are joined, each must have the same form — all infinitives, all gerunds, or all finite verbs.</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex wrong-ex">✗ "The goal is to reduce costs, improving efficiency, and the elimination of waste."</div>
      <div class="pattern-ex right-ex">✓ "The goal is to reduce costs, improve efficiency, and eliminate waste."</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The four contexts where parallelism is tested</div>
  <div class="context-list">
    <div class="context-item">
      <div class="context-num">1</div>
      <div class="context-body">
        <strong>Lists of three or more items</strong> — the most common SAT pattern. The last item in a list is almost always where the error hides, since the first two items establish the pattern and the third breaks it.
        <div class="context-ex">✗ "The report evaluated costs, timelines, and what the staffing requirements were."<br>✓ "The report evaluated costs, timelines, and staffing requirements."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="context-item">
      <div class="context-num">2</div>
      <div class="context-body">
        <strong>Paired conjunctions</strong> — whatever grammatical form follows the first conjunction must be repeated after the second. The SAT often places the error on the second element.
        <div class="context-ex">✗ "Either the committee will approve the plan or rejecting it outright."<br>✓ "Either the committee will approve the plan or reject it outright."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="context-item">
      <div class="context-num">3</div>
      <div class="context-body">
        <strong>Comparisons with "than" or "as…as"</strong> — both sides of the comparison must be grammatically equivalent. A common error is comparing a noun to a clause or a gerund to an infinitive.
        <div class="context-ex">✗ "Composting is more effective than when you use chemical fertilizers."<br>✓ "Composting is more effective than using chemical fertilizers."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="context-item">
      <div class="context-num">4</div>
      <div class="context-body">
        <strong>Clauses after "that"</strong> — when multiple clauses follow the same verb + "that," each clause must have the same structure. Dropping "that" before the second clause while keeping it before the first creates imbalance.
        <div class="context-ex">✗ "Researchers found that sleep deprivation reduces focus and productivity was impaired."<br>✓ "Researchers found that sleep deprivation reduces focus and that productivity was impaired."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="green-box">
    <div class="green-label">The quick parallelism test</div>
    <div class="green-text">When you spot a list or paired construction, identify the grammatical form of the first item — noun, infinitive, gerund, adjective, clause — then check every other item against it. If any item breaks the pattern, it's wrong. Ask: could I list all items together with "and" between each pair and have them all sound natural? If not, the structure is broken.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Find the first item first</div><div class="tip-body">The first item in any list or paired construction sets the pattern. Never change it — only fix the items that deviate from its form.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Label each item's form</div><div class="tip-body">Mentally tag each item: noun? infinitive? gerund? adjective? clause? If any tag differs from the others, that item needs to be rewritten to match.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Watch for "to" in infinitive lists</div><div class="tip-body">Once "to" is established before the first infinitive, subsequent infinitives can drop "to" (share the first one). But you cannot switch from infinitive to gerund mid-list.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Paired conjunctions demand exact symmetry</div><div class="tip-body">"Not only X but also Y" — X and Y must be the same form. Read what immediately follows each conjunction and compare them directly.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

