<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 2 · Lesson 2.16</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Modifiers</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to place modifying phrases next to the noun they describe — and to fix the two classic modifier errors the SAT tests: dangling modifiers and misplaced modifiers.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The two modifier errors</div>
  <div class="body-text">A modifier is any word, phrase, or clause that describes or limits another element in a sentence. The rule is simple: a modifier must be placed as <strong>close as possible</strong> to what it modifies. When it isn't, two types of errors result.</div>
  <div class="error-grid">
    <div class="error-card" style="background:#FCEBEB;">
      <div class="error-title" style="color:#A32D2D;">Dangling modifier</div>
      <div class="error-def" style="color:#501313;">The noun being modified is absent from the sentence or is not the subject immediately following the modifier. The modifier "dangles" with nothing logical to attach to.</div>
      <div class="error-ex" style="color:#712B13;">
        ✗ "Having studied all night, the exam seemed easy."<br>
        <span style="font-size:11px;">(Who studied all night? Not "the exam" — but "the exam" is the subject.)</span><br><br>
        ✓ "Having studied all night, <strong>she</strong> found the exam easy."<br>
        ✓ "Because <strong>she</strong> had studied all night, the exam seemed easy."
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="error-card" style="background:#FAEEDA;">
      <div class="error-title" style="color:#854F0B;">Misplaced modifier</div>
      <div class="error-def" style="color:#633806;">The noun being modified is present in the sentence, but the modifier is positioned too far away — or next to the wrong noun — creating an unintended meaning.</div>
      <div class="error-ex" style="color:#633806;">
        ✗ "The scientist observed the cells using a microscope that were dividing rapidly."<br>
        <span style="font-size:11px;">("that were dividing rapidly" modifies "microscope," not "cells")</span><br><br>
        ✓ "Using a microscope, the scientist observed the cells that were dividing rapidly."
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The three most common modifier patterns on the SAT</div>
  <div class="rule-list">
    <div class="rule-item">
      <div class="rule-num">1</div>
      <div class="rule-body">
        <strong>Introductory participial phrase</strong> — an -ing or -ed phrase at the start of a sentence must modify the subject of the main clause. The subject immediately following the comma must be the person or thing performing the action in the phrase.
        <div class="rule-ex">✗ "Painted in vibrant colors, visitors admired the mural." (Visitors weren't painted.)<br>✓ "Painted in vibrant colors, the mural attracted admiring visitors."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-item">
      <div class="rule-num">2</div>
      <div class="rule-body">
        <strong>Introductory prepositional or appositive phrase</strong> — a phrase at the start that describes a person, place, or thing must be immediately followed by that noun as the subject.
        <div class="rule-ex">✗ "As a leading expert in linguistics, her research has been widely cited." ("her research" is not an expert)<br>✓ "As a leading expert in linguistics, she has seen her research widely cited."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-item">
      <div class="rule-num">3</div>
      <div class="rule-body">
        <strong>Mid-sentence relative clause</strong> — a "which," "who," or "that" clause must be placed immediately after the noun it modifies, not separated by other clauses that make the reference ambiguous.
        <div class="rule-ex">✗ "She gave the report to her manager, which described quarterly losses." ("which" seems to modify "manager")<br>✓ "She gave her manager the report, which described quarterly losses."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="fix-box">
    <div class="fix-label">Two ways to fix a dangling modifier</div>
    <div class="fix-text"><strong>Fix 1 — Change the subject:</strong> Make the subject of the main clause the same person/thing as the actor in the modifier.<br>"Having analyzed the data, <em>the researchers</em> drew their conclusions." ✓<br><br><strong>Fix 2 — Rewrite the modifier as a clause:</strong> Turn the introductory phrase into a full subordinate clause with its own subject.<br>"After <em>the researchers</em> analyzed the data, they drew their conclusions." ✓</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check the subject after every opening phrase</div><div class="tip-body">Whenever a sentence opens with a phrase before the main clause, immediately ask: does the subject of the main clause logically perform the action described in the opening phrase? If not, it's a dangling modifier.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Ask "who is doing this?" for -ing phrases</div><div class="tip-body">For any participial phrase (-ing or -ed), ask who is actually performing that action. The answer must be the subject of the sentence's main clause — if it isn't, the modifier dangles.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Place "only," "almost," "just" carefully</div><div class="tip-body">Single-word modifiers like "only," "almost," "just," and "nearly" must be placed directly before the word they modify. "I only eat fish on Fridays" vs. "I eat only fish on Fridays" — very different meanings.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Move relative clauses next to their noun</div><div class="tip-body">For misplaced "which/who/that" clauses, the fix is almost always to rearrange the sentence so the clause immediately follows its antecedent noun, not another noun that happens to be nearby.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

