<!-- Q1 -->
<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a history essay on Marie Curie</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span><span class="ul">Having won the Nobel Prize in both Physics and Chemistry, no other scientist in history has achieved this distinction.</span> Curie's work on radioactivity transformed not only physics and chemistry but also medicine, where radioactive isotopes she identified became foundational tools for cancer treatment and medical imaging.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">5</span>Despite facing significant gender discrimination throughout her career, she continued to conduct groundbreaking research and mentor the next generation of scientists until her death in 1934.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Modifiers</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which choice most effectively corrects the <strong>dangling modifier</strong> in the underlined sentence?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Having won the Nobel Prize in both Physics and Chemistry, no other scientist in history has achieved this distinction.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Having won the Nobel Prize in both Physics and Chemistry, Marie Curie achieved a distinction no other scientist in history has matched.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The Nobel Prize having been won in both Physics and Chemistry, no other scientist in history has achieved this distinction.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Having won the Nobel Prize in both Physics and Chemistry is a distinction no other scientist in history has achieved.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> The opening phrase "Having won the Nobel Prize in both Physics and Chemistry" describes Marie Curie — she won the prizes. The subject immediately following must be Curie. Option B correctly places "Marie Curie" as the subject: "Having won…, Marie Curie achieved a distinction." Option A keeps "no other scientist" as the subject — but "no other scientist" didn't win the prizes, Curie did. Option C turns the phrase into an awkward passive construction that still doesn't name Curie as subject. Option D converts the phrase into a gerund subject, losing the sentence's intended meaning.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The opening phrase says someone won two Nobel Prizes. Who did that? Marie Curie. The subject immediately after the comma must be Curie — not "no other scientist." Which option places "Marie Curie" as the subject right after the opening phrase?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a scientific article on deep-sea exploration</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>The submersible descended slowly toward the ocean floor, carrying a team of three researchers. <span class="ul">Equipped with high-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors, the scientific data collected during the dive would be analyzed for months afterward.</span><br><br>
        <span class="ln">5</span>At a depth of 4,000 meters, the team encountered a previously undocumented species of bioluminescent jellyfish — a discovery that would later appear in three peer-reviewed journals and attract significant media coverage.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Modifiers</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which choice most effectively corrects the <strong>dangling modifier</strong> in the underlined sentence?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Equipped with high-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors, the scientific data collected during the dive would be analyzed for months afterward.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Equipped with high-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors, the submersible collected scientific data that would be analyzed for months afterward.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The scientific data, equipped with high-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors, would be analyzed for months after the dive.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>High-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors equipped the submersible, and the scientific data would be analyzed for months afterward.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "Equipped with high-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors" describes the submersible — the submersible is the thing equipped with those instruments, not "the scientific data." Option B correctly places "the submersible" as the subject: "Equipped with…, the submersible collected data." Option A keeps "the scientific data" as subject — data can't be equipped with cameras. Option C absurdly implies data is equipped with cameras. Option D fixes the logic but loses the participial opening structure and the sentence flows awkwardly.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> What is "equipped with high-resolution cameras and sensitive pressure sensors"? The submersible — not the data. The subject after the comma must be the thing that is equipped. Which option places "the submersible" immediately after the opening phrase?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a student essay on behavioral economics</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>Researchers presented participants with two retirement savings plans in the study <span class="ul">that demonstrated the power of default options</span>. Plan A automatically enrolled employees unless they opted out; Plan B required active enrollment. Enrollment rates were 85% under Plan A and only 40% under Plan B — a gap driven entirely by which option was set as the default, not by any difference in the plans' actual benefits.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">7</span>The finding confirmed what behavioral economists had long argued: that people tend to accept whatever option requires the least effort, regardless of whether it serves their long-term interests.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Modifiers</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which choice corrects the <strong>misplaced modifier</strong> in the underlined portion?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Researchers presented participants with two retirement savings plans in the study that demonstrated the power of default options.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>In the study that demonstrated the power of default options, researchers presented participants with two retirement savings plans.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>Researchers, in the study that demonstrated the power of default options, presented participants with two retirement savings plans.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Researchers presented participants in the study that demonstrated the power of default options with two retirement savings plans.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> The clause "that demonstrated the power of default options" is meant to describe the study — but in the original, it's positioned right after "plans," implying the plans demonstrated the power of default options. Option B moves the entire phrase "in the study that demonstrated the power of default options" to the front of the sentence, where it clearly modifies the context of what the researchers did, and "the study" is properly connected to its relative clause. Option C places the modifier inside the main clause next to "researchers," which is awkward. Option D puts the clause after "participants in the study," implying the participants demonstrated default option power.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The clause "that demonstrated the power of default options" should describe the study, not the plans or the participants. Which option repositions the phrase so that "the study" is immediately followed by "that demonstrated…," making the reference unambiguous?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

