<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 2 · Lesson 2.17</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Possessives & Apostrophes</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master every apostrophe rule — possessives for singular and plural nouns, contractions, and the possessive pronouns that never take apostrophes.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>10 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The complete apostrophe ruleset</div>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Case</th><th>Rule</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Singular noun possession</td><td>Add 's — always, even if the noun ends in s</td><td><em>the student's essay / the class's average / James's discovery</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Plural noun ending in s</td><td>Add apostrophe only (after the s)</td><td><em>the students' essays / the scientists' findings</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Plural noun NOT ending in s</td><td>Add 's</td><td><em>the children's books / the people's choice / the women's team</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Contraction</td><td>Apostrophe replaces omitted letters</td><td><em>it's (it is/has) / they're (they are) / who's (who is/has) / don't (do not)</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Possessive pronouns</td><td>NEVER take apostrophes</td><td><em>its / their / whose / your / our / hers / his / ours / theirs</em></td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The four pairs the SAT always confuses</div>
  <div class="confuse-grid">
    <div class="confuse-card">
      <div class="confuse-title">its vs. it's</div>
      <div class="confuse-rule"><strong>its</strong> = possessive pronoun (belonging to it). <strong>it's</strong> = contraction of "it is" or "it has." Test: can you substitute "it is"? If yes → it's. If no → its.</div>
      <div class="confuse-ex">✓ "The study and its findings were clear." (possessive)<br>✓ "It's been proven that sleep matters." (it has)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="confuse-card">
      <div class="confuse-title">their vs. they're vs. there</div>
      <div class="confuse-rule"><strong>their</strong> = possessive (belonging to them). <strong>they're</strong> = they are. <strong>there</strong> = location or existential ("there is"). All sound identical — context is the only guide.</div>
      <div class="confuse-ex">✓ "Their results were published." (possessive)<br>✓ "They're ready to present." (they are)<br>✓ "There are three approaches." (existential)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="confuse-card">
      <div class="confuse-title">whose vs. who's</div>
      <div class="confuse-rule"><strong>whose</strong> = possessive relative pronoun. <strong>who's</strong> = contraction of "who is" or "who has." Test: substitute "who is." If it works → who's. If not → whose.</div>
      <div class="confuse-ex">✓ "The researcher whose paper was cited…" (possessive)<br>✓ "The scientist who's leading the team…" (who is)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="confuse-card">
      <div class="confuse-title">your vs. you're</div>
      <div class="confuse-rule"><strong>your</strong> = possessive (belonging to you). <strong>you're</strong> = contraction of "you are." Test: substitute "you are." If it works → you're. If not → your.</div>
      <div class="confuse-ex">✓ "Your analysis was thorough." (possessive)<br>✓ "You're the lead author." (you are)</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="test-box">
    <div class="test-label">The ownership test for apostrophes in nouns</div>
    <div class="test-text">Before adding an apostrophe to a noun, ask: does this noun own something? Rephrase using "of": <em>"the findings of the study"</em> → <em>"the study's findings"</em> ✓. If the noun is just a simple plural with no ownership — <em>"three studies were published"</em> — no apostrophe. Plurals without possession never take apostrophes.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Expand every contraction to test</div><div class="tip-body">For any word with an apostrophe, try expanding it: "it's" → "it is/has," "who's" → "who is/has," "they're" → "they are." If the expansion sounds wrong in context, you need the possessive form without an apostrophe.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Possessive pronouns never use apostrophes</div><div class="tip-body">Its, their, whose, your, our, hers, his, ours, theirs — none of these ever take an apostrophe. If you see "it's" used as a possessive, it's always wrong.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check: is the noun plural or possessive?</div><div class="tip-body">Many SAT errors involve adding apostrophes to simple plurals. "The results shows…" → "results" is a plural, not a possessive — no apostrophe needed. Only add apostrophes when something belongs to the noun.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Plural possessive: find the plural first</div><div class="tip-body">For plural possessives, first form the plural, then add the apostrophe. Students → students' (apostrophe after the s). Children → children's (irregular plural, so add 's). Never add 's to an already-plural noun ending in s.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

