</div>

<!-- Q1 -->
<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a scientific article on migratory bird patterns</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>Biologists studying long-distance bird migration have found that a <span class="ul">species'</span> ability to navigate thousands of miles with remarkable precision depends on multiple sensory systems working in concert. The birds use the position of the sun, the pattern of stars, and Earth's magnetic field — a redundancy that makes their navigation robust even when one system is disrupted.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">6</span>Recent research suggests that some species can also detect polarized light at dawn and dusk, giving them additional calibration points that help maintain accuracy across entire hemispheres.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Possessives</div>
      <div class="q-text">Is the apostrophe placement in <strong>"species'"</strong> correct, and why?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Yes — "species" is a plural noun ending in s, so the apostrophe correctly follows the s.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>No — it should be "species's" because "species" is a singular noun.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>No — it should be "specieses'" because a plural ending must be formed first.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>No — possessive pronouns never take apostrophes, so "species'" is always wrong.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "Species" is a singular noun (it refers to one species). The singular possessive is formed by adding 's: "species's ability." However, many style guides — and the SAT — accept "species'" for singular nouns already ending in s, particularly for words where the extra syllable would be awkward. In this context, Option B is the most technically precise answer: "species" here is singular, and the possessive of a singular noun ending in s is "species's." Option A would be correct only if "species" were plural. Option C invents a non-word. Option D confuses nouns with pronouns.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Is "species" singular or plural in this sentence? It refers to one type of bird — singular. For a singular noun, the possessive is formed with 's, not just an apostrophe after s. Which option identifies the correct form for a singular noun ending in s?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a student essay on urban food deserts</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>In many low-income urban neighborhoods, <span class="ul">residents' access</span> to fresh produce is severely limited by the absence of full-service grocery stores within walking distance. Corner stores and fast-food outlets fill the gap, but <span class="ul">their</span> offerings are typically high in sodium, sugar, and saturated fat — contributing to elevated rates of diet-related illness in the communities <span class="ul">they're</span> meant to serve.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">6</span>Policy solutions range from zoning incentives for grocery stores to subsidized farmers' markets, but implementation has been slow and uneven across cities.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Possessives & Contractions</div>
      <div class="q-text">The passage uses three underlined forms: <strong>"residents' access," "their," and "they're."</strong> Which assessment is correct?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>All three are correct as written.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>"residents' access" should be "resident's access" because only one resident is implied.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>"their" should be "they're" because it refers to the stores' actions.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>"they're" should be "their" because it shows possession of the communities.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> All three forms are correctly used. "Residents' access" — plural possessive (many residents share limited access), apostrophe after s ✓. "Their offerings" — possessive pronoun referring to corner stores and fast-food outlets, no apostrophe ✓. "They're meant to serve" — contraction of "they are" (the stores are meant to serve the communities) ✓. Option B is wrong — the passage clearly refers to multiple residents. Option C confuses possessive "their" with contraction "they're" — the stores' offerings belong to them, not a verb action. Option D reverses the error — "they're" here is indeed "they are," which is correct.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Test each form: (1) "residents' access" — one resident or many? (2) "their offerings" — does this show possession or describe an action? Try expanding: "they are offerings" — does that work? (3) "they're meant to serve" — expand: "they are meant to serve" — does that work? Evaluate all three before choosing.</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a history essay on the Apollo program</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>The engineers <span class="ul">who's</span> designs made the Moon landing possible came from extraordinarily diverse backgrounds — mathematicians, aeronautical engineers, former military pilots, and self-taught programmers among them. Many were women, particularly in the computing divisions, <span class="ul">whose</span> calculations provided the navigational precision the missions required.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">6</span>Despite <span class="ul">their</span> essential contributions, many of these engineers received little public recognition during their lifetimes, overshadowed by the astronauts who carried out the missions they designed.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Possessives</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which underlined word is used <strong>incorrectly</strong>, and what should it be?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>"who's" — should be "whose" (possessive, not contraction)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>"whose" — should be "who's" (contraction of "who has")</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>"their" — should be "they're" (contraction of "they are")</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>All three are used correctly.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "Who's designs" — expand "who's": "who is designs" or "who has designs" — neither makes sense. The sentence needs the possessive: "whose designs." "Whose" (second use) — the women's calculations provided navigational precision. Expand "whose": "who is calculations" — nonsense. Possessive "whose" is correct ✓. "Their essential contributions" — possessive pronoun referring to the engineers' contributions ✓. The only error is the first "who's," which must be "whose" — a possessive relative pronoun showing that the designs belong to the engineers.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Test each underlined word. For "who's" — expand it: "who is designs" or "who has designs." Does either make sense in the sentence? If not, you need the possessive "whose." Check the other two the same way.</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

