<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 2 · Lesson 2.18</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Commonly Confused Words</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the word pairs that sound similar but mean different things — the last category of grammar errors the SAT tests, and one of the most reliable sources of points.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>10 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The 12 most tested word pairs on the SAT</div>
  <div class="word-grid">
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">affect vs. effect</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>affect</strong> = verb (to influence). <strong>effect</strong> = noun (a result). Exception: "to effect change" = to bring about (rare verb use).</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "Stress affects sleep quality." / "The effect was immediate."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">fewer vs. less</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>fewer</strong> = countable nouns (items you can count). <strong>less</strong> = uncountable nouns (amounts, qualities, abstractions).</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "Fewer studies / less research." / "Fewer hours / less time."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">among vs. between</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>between</strong> = two items (or a precise relationship). <strong>among</strong> = three or more items (a general group).</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "Between the two options." / "Among the four candidates."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">that vs. which</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>that</strong> = restrictive clauses (essential, no commas). <strong>which</strong> = nonrestrictive clauses (extra info, with commas).</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "The study that won the prize…" / "The study, which lasted five years,…"</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">imply vs. infer</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>imply</strong> = to suggest (the speaker/writer implies). <strong>infer</strong> = to conclude (the reader/listener infers).</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "The data implies a correlation." / "Readers can infer the cause."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">amount vs. number</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>amount</strong> = uncountable quantities. <strong>number</strong> = countable items. Parallel to less/fewer.</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "A large amount of funding." / "A large number of studies."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">comprise vs. compose</div>
      <div class="word-defs">The whole <strong>comprises</strong> the parts. The parts <strong>compose</strong> the whole. Never "comprised of" — always "comprises."</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "The report comprises five sections." / "Five sections compose the report."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">principle vs. principal</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>principle</strong> = a fundamental rule or belief (noun). <strong>principal</strong> = main/primary (adjective) or head of a school (noun).</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "A core principle of ethics." / "The principal investigator."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">assure vs. ensure vs. insure</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>assure</strong> = reassure a person. <strong>ensure</strong> = guarantee an outcome. <strong>insure</strong> = financial insurance only.</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "She assured him it was safe." / "Steps to ensure accuracy."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">since vs. because</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>since</strong> = from a point in time (or weak causal). <strong>because</strong> = the direct cause. Use "because" when stating an explicit reason.</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "Since 2010, rates have risen." / "Rates rose because of policy changes."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">continual vs. continuous</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>continual</strong> = recurring with interruptions. <strong>continuous</strong> = uninterrupted, without pause.</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "Continual interruptions." / "A continuous data stream."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="word-card">
      <div class="word-pair">precede vs. proceed</div>
      <div class="word-defs"><strong>precede</strong> = to come before. <strong>proceed</strong> = to continue forward.</div>
      <div class="word-ex">✓ "Discovery precedes application." / "The team proceeded to publish."</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="test-box">
    <div class="test-label">Context substitution test</div>
    <div class="test-text">For any confused word pair, replace the underlined word with your candidate and read the full sentence. Ask: does the substitute carry the exact meaning the sentence requires? A word can "sound right" while meaning something subtly different. For affect/effect, ask: is this a verb describing an action (affect) or a noun describing a result (effect)?</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Affect/effect: default to noun "effect"</div><div class="tip-body">In the vast majority of SAT questions, "effect" is the noun and "affect" is the verb. If the word follows an article (the, an, a) or adjective — it's a noun → use "effect." If it follows a subject and means "to influence" — it's a verb → use "affect."</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Fewer/less — the checkout lane test</div><div class="tip-body">If you can count individual items ("10 items or fewer"), use "fewer." If you measure a bulk amount ("less flour," "less time"), use "less." When in doubt, ask: can I count them one by one?</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">That vs. which — the comma test</div><div class="tip-body">If the clause has commas around it → use "which." If there are no commas and the clause is essential to identifying the noun → use "that." You can't use "that" after a comma — the SAT will test this.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Imply vs. infer — sender vs. receiver</div><div class="tip-body">The writer/speaker implies; the reader/listener infers. If the subject of the verb is a text, study, or speaker — use "imply." If the subject is a person drawing a conclusion from evidence — use "infer."</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

