<!-- Q1 -->
<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a scientific article on antibiotic resistance</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>The overuse of antibiotics has a profound <span class="ul">affect</span> on the evolution of bacterial populations. When antibiotics eliminate susceptible bacteria, resistant strains survive and reproduce — a process <span class="ul">that</span> accelerates when treatment courses are interrupted or when antibiotics are prescribed unnecessarily.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">5</span>Researchers emphasize that the <span class="ul">principal</span> challenge is not scientific but behavioral: persuading both physicians and patients to use antibiotics only when genuinely required.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Confused Words</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which underlined word is used <strong>incorrectly</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>"affect" — should be "effect" (a noun, not a verb, is needed here)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>"that" — should be "which" (the clause provides extra information)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>"principal" — should be "principle" (a fundamental rule, not "main")</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>All three are used correctly.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "A profound affect" — "affect" follows the indefinite article "a" and is used as a noun. But "affect" is almost always a verb. The noun form is "effect": "a profound effect on bacterial populations." ✓ "that accelerates" — the clause "that accelerates when…" is restrictive (it identifies which process), so "that" with no commas is correct ✓. "The principal challenge" — "principal" as an adjective means "main" or "primary," which is exactly the meaning needed here ✓. Only "affect" is wrong.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Test each: (1) "a profound affect" — is a noun or verb needed after "a profound"? What part of speech follows an article? (2) "that accelerates" — is this clause restrictive or nonrestrictive? Does it have commas? (3) "the principal challenge" — does this mean "main challenge" or "a fundamental rule"?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from an economics essay on income inequality</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>Economic mobility in the United States has declined over the past fifty years, with <span class="ul">less</span> Americans now able to surpass the income level of their parents than at any point since records began. The gap between the wealthiest and poorest households has widened considerably, and researchers <span class="ul">infer</span> that this trend will continue unless structural changes are made to education funding and tax policy.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">6</span>The data, <span class="ul">which</span> spans four decades of household income surveys, provides a comprehensive picture of how mobility has shifted across generations.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Confused Words</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which underlined word is used <strong>incorrectly</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>"less" — should be "fewer" (Americans are countable individuals)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>"infer" — should be "imply" (researchers are suggesting, not concluding)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>"which" — should be "that" (the clause is essential to identifying the data)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>All three are used correctly.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "Less Americans" — Americans are countable individuals. The correct word for countable nouns is "fewer": "fewer Americans" ✓. "Researchers infer" — researchers are drawing a conclusion from the data they have analyzed, which is the definition of "infer" (to conclude from evidence). "Imply" would mean the researchers were merely suggesting without stating directly, but the sentence says they are concluding from the trend ✓ — actually "infer" is correct here. "Which spans" — the clause "which spans four decades" is set off by a comma and provides extra information about the data, making "which" correct ✓. Only "less" is wrong — it should be "fewer."</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Test each: (1) "less Americans" — can you count Americans individually? Countable → fewer or less? (2) "researchers infer" — are researchers drawing a conclusion from evidence, or are they suggesting something? (3) "which spans" — does this clause have a comma before it? Is it extra information or essential identification?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="sat-layout">
    <div class="passage-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Passage</div>
      <div class="passage-source">Adapted from a biology article on ecosystem resilience</div>
      <div class="passage-text">
        <span class="ln">1</span>A healthy forest ecosystem <span class="ul">comprises</span> hundreds of interacting species, from the towering canopy trees to the microscopic fungi <span class="ul">that</span> form symbiotic networks in the soil. When one component is disrupted — by disease, invasive species, or human activity — the effects can cascade through the system in ways that are difficult to predict or <span class="ul">ensure</span>.<br><br>
        <span class="ln">6</span>Ecologists argue that maintaining biodiversity is the most reliable way to preserve a forest's capacity to absorb and recover from disturbance.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Confused Words</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which underlined word is used <strong>incorrectly</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>"comprises" — should be "is comprised of" (standard usage)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>"that" — should be "which" (the clause adds non-essential detail)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>"ensure" — should be "assure" (reassuring a person is intended)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>"ensure" — should be "reverse" or "control" (the sentence needs a word meaning to stop or manage the effects)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "Comprises" — the whole (a forest ecosystem) comprises the parts (hundreds of species). "Comprises" is correct; "comprised of" is considered an error in formal writing ✓. "That form symbiotic networks" — this clause is essential to identifying which specific fungi are meant (not just any fungi — the ones that form networks). No comma, restrictive → "that" is correct ✓. "Difficult to predict or ensure" — "ensure" means to guarantee an outcome. But the sentence says the effects are hard to predict or [stop/reverse/control]. "Ensure" doesn't mean to stop or manage something — it guarantees it. The correct word here would be something like "reverse" or "control." Option D correctly identifies this as the error and names an appropriate replacement.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Test each: (1) "comprises" — does the whole comprise the parts, or do the parts comprise the whole? (2) "that form networks" — is this an essential identifying clause with no commas? (3) "difficult to predict or ensure" — what does "ensure" mean? Does that meaning fit here — can you "ensure" cascading effects, or do you want to stop/control them?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'D')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

