<div class="tag">Reading & Writing · Module 2 · Lesson 2.14</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Verb Tense, Mood & Voice</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to keep tense consistent, choose the correct mood for hypothetical statements, and fix voice inconsistencies in parallel structures.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The three verb properties the SAT tests</div>
  <div class="body-text"><strong>Tense</strong> places an action in time. <strong>Mood</strong> expresses whether a statement is fact, command, or hypothetical. <strong>Voice</strong> determines whether the subject acts or is acted upon.</div>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Tense</th><th>When to use</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Simple present</td><td>General truths, current states</td><td><em>Scientists study climate data.</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Simple past</td><td>Completed past actions</td><td><em>The team published in 2019.</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Present perfect</td><td>Past with present relevance</td><td><em>Researchers have documented a 40% decline.</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Past perfect</td><td>Earlier of two past events</td><td><em>By launch, the population had already declined.</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Literary present</td><td>Discussing texts, arguments, findings</td><td><em>Darwin argues that selection drives adaptation.</em></td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title">Subjunctive mood</div>
      <div class="mini-body">Used for hypotheticals, wishes, recommendations. Triggers: if, wish, suggest, recommend, require, insist.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">✓ "If the model <strong>were</strong> accurate…" (not "was")<br>✓ "The committee recommended she <strong>be</strong> appointed."<br>✓ "I wish the data <strong>were</strong> complete."</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title">Active vs. passive voice</div>
      <div class="mini-body">Both are grammatically correct. The SAT only tests passive when it breaks a parallel structure — mixing active and passive verbs in the same construction.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">✗ Mixed: "Scientists discovered X and Y was identified by them."<br>✓ Parallel active: "Scientists discovered X and identified Y."</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="trap-box">
    <div class="trap-label">Two most common SAT traps</div>
    <div class="trap-text"><strong>Trap 1 — Unnecessary tense shift:</strong> A past-tense passage suddenly uses present tense. Always match the established timeline.<br><br><strong>Trap 2 — "Was" instead of "were" in subjunctive:</strong> Any contrary-to-fact conditional requires "were": "If the sample <em>were</em> larger…" / "If I <em>were</em> you…"</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Establish the base tense first</div><div class="tip-body">Read surrounding sentences. What tense does the passage use throughout? The answer must match unless there's a clear logical reason to shift.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Spot subjunctive triggers</div><div class="tip-body">The moment you see "if," "wish," "suggest," "recommend," or "require" — check: real condition or hypothetical? Real → indicative. Hypothetical → subjunctive ("were," "be").</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Literary present for texts</div><div class="tip-body">When discussing a book, study, or theory, always use present tense: "Shakespeare depicts ambition as destructive" — even for centuries-old works.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Past perfect = "had + verb"</div><div class="tip-body">When two past events are described and one came first, the earlier one needs "had + past participle" to show the sequence clearly.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

